.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Abernethy was born in 1300, in Abernethy, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Alexander de Abernethy, was 29 and her mother, Margaret de Menteith, was 25. She married John Stewart 1st Earl of Angus on 24 October 1328, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1370, in Angus, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1300–1370":"1300–1370","1289–1355":"1289–1355","1293–Female":"1293–Surnud","1305–Female":"1305–Surnud","1307–Female":"1307–Surnud","1294–1331":"1294–1331","1331–1361":"1331–1361","1271–1315":"1271–1315","1276–1325":"1276–1325","9 December 1331":"9. detsember 1331","1361":"1361","1294":"1294","24 October 1328":"24. oktoober 1328","1370":"1370","1271":"1271","1293":"1293","1305":"1305","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1300":"1300","1355":"1355","1289":"1289","1331":"1331","1276":"1276","Abt 1290":"umbes 1290","1307":"1307","Scotland":"Scotland","Abernethy, Perthshire, Scotland":"Abernethy, Perthshire, Scotland","Angusshire, Scotland":"Angus, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Abernathy, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Abernethy, Inverness-shire, Scotland","Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Scotland":"Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1300–1370":"1300–1370","1289–1355":"1289–1355","1293–Female":"1293–Kuollut","1305–Female":"1305–Kuollut","1307–Female":"1307–Kuollut","1294–1331":"1294–1331","1331–1361":"1331–1361","1271–1315":"1271–1315","1276–1325":"1276–1325","9 December 1331":"9. joulukuuta 1331","1361":"1361","1294":"1294","24 October 1328":"24. lokakuuta 1328","1370":"1370","1271":"1271","1293":"1293","1305":"1305","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1300":"1300","1355":"1355","1289":"1289","1331":"1331","1276":"1276","Abt 1290":"noin 1290","1307":"1307","Scotland":"Scotland","Abernethy, Perthshire, Scotland":"